---
title: "Option Basics"
---

## Start Here

- An _option_ is a (_derivative_) contract whose value is derived from the value of the underlying.
- Similar to a contract to buy a house, an option contract specifies a date and a price.
- The price specified on the option contract is called the _strike_, and the date is called the _expiry_.
- The strike specifies the price the underlying security will be exchanged, and the expiry specifies the last date the contract is effective.
- Two types of option contracts exist: a _call_ option, and a _put_ option.
- For example, a call option contract for the underlying $AAPL stock, with an expiry of May 21, 2021 and a strike price of $130, is a contract that gives the buyer the right (but not the obligation) to purchase (from the seller of the call option) 100 x $AAPL stocks for $130 each,  on or before the expiry date of May 21, 2021
- For this right to buy the underlying $AAPL stocks at a potentially discounted value, the buyer of the call option contract pays a _premium_ to the seller of the option.
- The put option, on the otherhand, gives the buyer the right (but not he obligation) to sell the underlying for the specified strike price, on or before the expiry date. Again, a _premium_ is paid to obtain such rights.
- When the holder of an option contracts wishes to _exercise_ their rights (on or before the expiry), the writer (seller) of the option contract is _assigned_ and  obliged to sell (in the case of a call contract) or buy (in the case of a put contract) 100x of the underlying to/from the owner of the contract.

## Premium

- Option contracts provides buyers with rights, and locks in sellers with obligations.
- Therefore, the buyer of the rights pays a premium to the seller of the obligations.
- There are two components to the value (premium) of an options contract: _intrinsic_ value and _extrinsic_ value (aka time value).
- An option contract only have instrinsic value if its strike price is above (in the case of a call option) the strike price, or below (in the case of a put option) the strike price.
- When an option has intrinsic value, it is _ITM (In the Money)_, when the underlying security's price is just equal to the option's strike price, it is _ATM (At the Money)_. Otherwise the option is _OTM (Out of the Money)_.

### Parity Graphs

At _expiry_, the extrinsic value of an option is 0, so the value of the option is soley given by the intrinsic value.  

We can use _parity graphs_ to visualize:  

![parity long call](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

- parity graph of a long call, notice when underlying value > exercise price, for every $1 increment in the underlying price, the option value increase by $1.

![parity short call](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

- parity graph of a short call, notice when underlying $price > exercise price, for every $1 increment in the underlying price, the option value decreases by $1.

- For a call contract, when the value of the underlying is less than (or equal to) the strike price, the intrinsic value is 0 - since the option holder can purchase the underlying for less on the spot market.
- The extrinsinc value is determined by many factors such as: time to expiry (interest), risk/probability (volatility), underlying price deviation from strike price, supply/demand (of the options contract)
